results.description: Body length approx 50-60 cm estimated for moving animal. Habitat in disturbed ground by road along fast river with riverine forest.

comments.body: It's a pit viper (genus Protobothrops), though not sure on the species. Could be Protobothrops jerdonii

@ong-siau-kun Thank you for this suggested new identification, which is different from the ID agreed by 4 other people.  Is *Protobothrops xiangchengensis* a synonym for *Protobothrops jerdonii* or a new name for  (perhaps) a subspecies of *Protobothrops jerdonii*? Please would you explain the diagnostic features of *Protobothrops xiangchengensis* which distinguish it from *Protobothrops jerdonii*.
感谢您提出这个建议的新身份证明，该身份证明与其他4个人所同意的ID不同。 *象鼻原生动物*是*耶氏疟原虫*的同义词还是（也许）*耶氏疟原虫*的亚种的新名称？ 请您解释一下湘香原种*的诊断特征，使其区别于杰氏原种*。
Based on locality, P. xiangchengensis is a possibility.

@ong-siau-kun @guliwu_island @prakrit @tom-kirschey-nabu This a big change from the earlier consensus of *Protobothrops jerdonii* for this observation. I am guessing that there has been a taxonomic revision resulting in the emergence of *Protobothrops xiangchengensis*.  Please can one / some of you educate me on what has happened?  Many thanks for your time: I am always eager to learn. Thisis now superceded by my following comments.

results.place_guess: River valley ca. 50 km W of Danba (Sichuan) on road towards Luhuo

identifications.body: @ong-siau-kun @guliwu_island @prakrit @tom-kirschey-nabu The relevant source would seem to be: Peng Guo et al. (2016) "Multilocus phylogeny of the Asian Lance-headed pitvipers (Squamata, Viperidae, Protobothrops)" Zootaxa 4093 (3): 382–390. My observation was made close to N30.575° E101.646°. Applying this location to the species distribution map (Fig 1, p383) of Peng Guo et al. (2016) places it within the small mapped range of *Protobothrops xiangchengensis*, but also not far from the much wider mapped range of *Protobothrops jerdonii*.  Peng Guo et al. (2016) make clear that their mapped species ranges are "approximate" (in caption to map p383), & it is clear that  *Protobothrops jerdonii* & *Protobothrops xiangchengensis* are very closely related (Fig 2 p386).  Therefore it seems that opting for either  *Protobothrops jerdonii* or *Protobothrops xiangchengensis* is hardly justified without much more specific morphological information than is available from my observation.
